|referee    = \n|result     = \n}}\n\n=== U.S. Open Cup ===\n{{Main|2020 U.S. Open Cup}}\nMichigan will enter the 2020 U.S. Open Cup with the rest of the [[National Independent Soccer Association]] teams in the Second Round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nisasoccer.com/news/2019/12/13/lamar-hunt-us-open-cup-competition-format-announced|title=LAMAR HUNT U.S. OPEN CUP COMPETITION FORMAT ANNOUNCED|last=|first=|date=December 13, 2019|website=Nisasoccer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=RECORD-SETTING 100 TEAMS CONFIRMED FOR 2020 LAMAR HUNT U.S. OPEN CUP, 107TH EDITION OF U.S. SOCCER\u2019S NATIONAL CHAMPIONSHIP |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/01/record-setting-100-teams-confirmed-for-2020-lamar-hunt-us-open-cup |website=ussoccer.com |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> It was announced on January 29 that their first opponent would be [[USL Championship]] side [[Indy Eleven]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 U.S. OPEN CUP SECOND ROUND PAIRINGS AND HOST SCENARIOS |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/01/2020-us-open-cup-second-round-pairings-and-host-scenarios |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Football box collapsible\n|id         =\n|date       = April 8\n|time       = 7:00 pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|team1      = [[Indy Eleven]] (USLC) {{flagicon|Indiana}}\n|round      = [[2020 U.S. Open Cup#Second Round|Second Round]]\n|score      = P\u2013P\n|report     = \n|team2      = {{flagicon|Michigan}} [[Michigan Stars FC]] (NISA)\n|goals1     = \n|goals2     = \n|stadium    = [[IU Michael A. Carroll Track & Soccer Stadium|Carroll Stadium]]\n|location   = [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]]\n|attendance = \n|referee    = \n|result     = P\n|note       = On March 13, U.S. Soccer\u2019s Open Cup Committee announced the tournament would be temporarily suspended due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Soccer Temporarily Suspends 2020 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Due to Covid-19 Outbreak |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/03/us-soccer-temporarily-suspends-2020-lamar-hunt-us-open-cup-due-to-covid19-outbreak |website=www.ussoccer.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|stack = yes\n}}\n\n== Squad statistics ==\n{{Updated|Match played March 7, 2020}}\n\n=== Appearances and goals ===\n{{Extended football squad start|{{nobreak|[[2019-20 NISA season#Spring season|Spring Season]]}}|{{nobreak|[[2020 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]]}}}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"16\" style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"| Goalkeepers\n{{Extended football squad player|no=1|name=[[Arshia Aghababazadeh]]|pos=GK|nat=IRN|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=12|name=[[Sergio Orozco (soccer)|Sergio Orozco]]|pos=GK|nat=USA|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=16|name=[[Tatenda Mkuruva]]|pos=GK|nat=ZIM|0|0|-|-}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"16\" style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"| Defenders\n{{Extended football squad player|no=2|name=[[Tekodah Lobsiger]]|pos=DF|nat=USA|1|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=3|name=[[Gonnie Ben-Tal]]|pos=DF|nat=ISR|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=4|name=[[Robert Juncaj]]|pos=DF|nat=USA|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=5|name=[[Joseph Aidoo (footballer, born 1995)|Joseph Aidoo]]|pos=DF|nat=LBR|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=15|name=[[Andr\u00e9s Chalbaud]]|pos=DF|nat=VEN|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=17|name=[[Alexandre Frank]]|pos=DF|nat=FRA|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=19|name=[[Cameron Schneider]]|pos=DF|nat=USA|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=22|name=[[Adil Gowani]]|pos=DF|nat=USA|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=23|name=[[Patrick Sullivan (soccer)|Patrick Sullivan]]|pos=DF|nat=USA|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=25|name=[[James Abraham]]|pos=DF|nat=ENG|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=26|name=[[Terence Smith (soccer)|Terence Smith]]|pos=DF|nat=BAR|0|0|-|-}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"16\" style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"| Midfielders\n{{Extended football squad player|no=6|name=[[Remy Tazifor]]|pos=MF|nat=CMR|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=7|name=[[Steven Juncaj]]|pos=MF|nat=USA|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=8|name=[[Zanin Mahic]]|pos=MF|nat=BIH|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=9|name=[[Nenad Markovic (footballer)|Nenad Markovic]]|pos=MF|nat=SER|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=20|name=[[Nils Valdmanis]]|pos=MF|nat=LAT|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=21|name=[[Zachary Reynolds (soccer)|Zachary Reynolds]]|pos=MF|nat=USA|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=31|name=[[Jannik Eckenrode]]|pos=MF|nat=USA|1|0|-|-}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"16\" style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center\"| Forwards\n{{Extended football squad player|no=10|name=[[Kyle Nuel]]|pos=FW|nat=USA|2|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=11|name=[[Travis Ward (soccer)|Travis Ward]]|pos=FW|nat=USA|2|1|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=14|name=[[Alexander Satr\u00fastegui]]|pos=FW|nat=SPA|0|0|-|-}}\n{{Extended football squad player|no=29|name=[[James Pipe (soccer)|James Pipe]]|pos=FW|nat=USA|0|0|-|-}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Goal scorers===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=60|Place\n!width=60|Position\n!width=60|Nation\n!width=60|Number\n!width=150|Name\n!width=150|[[2019-20 NISA season#Spring season|Spring Season]]\n!width=150|[[2020 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]]\n!width=80|'''Total'''\n|-\n|1 ||FW||{{flagicon|USA}}||11||[[Travis Ward (soccer)|Travis Ward]]||1||-||1\n|-\n|}\n\n===Disciplinary record===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:10%; text-align:center;\"|'''Number'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|'''Nation'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|'''Position'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"width:30%; text-align:center;\"|'''Name'''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[2019-20 NISA season#Spring season|Spring Season]]'''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[2020 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]]'''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''Total'''\n|-\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#fe9;\"|{{yel}}\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#ff8888;\"|{{sent off}}\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#fe9;\"|{{yel}}\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#ff8888;\"|{{sent off}}\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#fe9;\"|{{yel}}\n!  style=\"width:60px; background:#ff8888;\"|{{sent off}}\n|-\n|8 ||{{flagicon|BIH}}||MF||[[Zanin Mahic]]||1||0||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|19 ||{{flagicon|USA}}||DF||[[Cameron Schneider]]||2||0||-||-||2||0\n|-\n|21 ||{{flagicon|USA}}||MF||[[Zachary Reynolds (soccer)|Zachary Reynolds]]||1||0||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|23 ||{{flagicon|USA}}||DF||[[Patrick Sullivan (soccer)|Patrick Sullivan]]||1||0||-||-||1||0\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2019\u201320 NISA season]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Independent Soccer Association}}\n{{2019\u201320 National Independent Soccer Association season by team}}\n{{2019 in American soccer}}\n{{2020 in American soccer}}\n\n[[Category:American soccer clubs 2019 season|Michigan Stars FC]]\n[[Category:American soccer clubs 2020 season|Michigan Stars FC]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in Michigan|Michigan Stars FC]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports in Michigan|Michigan Stars FC]]\n", "name_user": "ColeTrain4EVER", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_Michigan_Stars_FC_season"}
{"title_page": "Yanka Kupala", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = J\u00e1nka Kup\u00e1la<br>\u042f\u0301\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0430\n| image       = Yanka Kupala.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{OldStyleDate|July 7|1882|June 25}} \n| birth_place = [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], [[Minsk Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date  = June 28, 1942 (aged 59)\n| death_place = Moscow, [[Soviet Union]]\n| occupation  = Poet and writer\n| nationality = Belarusian\n| period      = 1903\u20131942\n}}\n\n'''Yanka Kupala''' (also spelled '''J\u00e1nka Kup\u00e1la''' or '''Janka Kupa\u0142a''', {{lang-be|\u042f\u0301\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0430}}; {{OldStyleDate|July 7|1882|June 25}} \u2013 June 28, 1942) \u2013 was the [[pen name]] of '''Iv\u00e1n Damin\u00edkavich Luts\u00e9vich''' (''Ivan Daminikavi\u010d \u0141ucevi\u010d'', {{lang-be|\u0406\u0432\u0430\u0301\u043d \u0414\u0430\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0301\u043a\u0430\u0432\u0456\u0447 \u041b\u0443\u0446\u044d\u0301\u0432\u0456\u0447}}), a [[Belarus]]ian poet and writer. Kupala is considered one of the greatest Belarusian-language writers of the 20th century.\n\n==Biography==\n{{unsourced|section|date=February 2017}}\n===Early life===\n[[Image:Yanka Kupala's House.JPG|thumb|left|House where Janka Kupala was born ([[folwark]] [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], [[Minsk district]], Belarus)]]\n[[Image:Yanka Kupala in Saint Petersburg, 1909.jpg|thumb|left|Janka Kupala during his study under professor A. Charniaev in [[Saint Petersburg]], 1909]]\nKupala was born on July 7, 1882 in [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], a [[folwark]] settlement near [[Maladzyechna]]. His family was noble, although both of Kupala's parents were employed as tenant farmers at the folwark. Kupala was thus essentially born into a landless peasant class. Kupala received a traditional Belarusian education, completing his studies in 1898. Following the death of his father in 1902, Kupala worked a variety of short-term jobs, including as a tutor, a shop assistant, and a record keeper.\n\nKupala's first serious literary attempt was ''Ziarno'', a Polish-language sentimental poem which he completed around 1903\u20131904 under the pseudonym \"K-a.\" His first Belarusian-language work (\"\u041c\u0430\u044f \u0434\u043e\u043b\u044f\") was dated July 15, 1904. Kupala's first published poem, \"\u041c\u0443\u0436\u044b\u043a\" (\"Peasant\"), was published approximately a year later, appearing in Belarusian in the Russophone Belarusian newspaper ''Severo-Zapadnyi Krai'' (''Northwestern [[Krai]]'') on May 11, 1905. A number of subsequent poems by Kupala appeared in the Belarusian-language newspaper ''[[Nasha Niva]]'' from 1906 to 1907.<ref>[http://archives.gov.by/eng/index.php?id=951386 Yanka Kupala: personality and work]</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nThe names of two women are still remembered when it comes to Yanka Kupala\u2019s personal life: Vladislava Stankevich (Vladislava Lutsevich)<ref>https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u041b\u0443\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447,_\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430_\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430</ref> and Paulina Miadzelka<ref>https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u041c\u044f\u0434\u0451\u043b\u043a\u0430,_\u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430_\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044c\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430</ref>. \nThe lead character of the play ''Paulinka'' was named after Paulina Miadzelka. At the age of 16, she went to Vilnya ([[Vilnius]]) in search of a better life. She met Yanka Kupala in 1909 at her friends\u2019 house. From her memoir ''\u0421\u0446\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0456 \u0436\u044b\u0446\u0446\u044f'' (''Paths of life''):\n\n\"Kupala was making jokes, asking if there are many beautiful girls in Vilnya. I frowned and kept silent, unhappy with the playful nature of the conversation.\"\n\nThe encounter with Paulina Miadzelka sank so deep into Kupala\u2019s mind that in four years he named his new play ''Paulinka'' and even invited Paulina Miadzelka to play a lead role in the similarly-named amateur play. The aspiring actress accepted the offer and kept communicating with the author, even though during one of the meetings she pushed him back with words \u201cAre you coming here to teach me how to kiss? I can manage without your lessons.\u201d<ref>https://sputnik.by/longrid/20170706/1029623359/yanka-kupala-tajny-zhizni-lyubvi-i-smerti.html</ref>\n\nYanka Kupala married Vladislava Stankevich in 1916 in St. Peter\u2019s and Paul\u2019s Cathedral in Moscow. There is a comment in Paulina Miadzelka\u2019s memoir that she learned about the marriage of Yanka Kupala and her friend only in a year after the ceremony. \nThe marriage of Yanka Kupala and Vladislava Lutsevich lasted for over 25 years. \nWhen the poet died in 1942, his always energetic wife took it very heavily. She decided to devote her life to preserving the memory of the great poet. It was Vladislava Lutsevich <ref>https://www.kp.by/daily/26624.5/3642327/</ref> who created and became the director of the Museum of Yanka Kupala<ref>https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439_\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0439_\u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439_\u042f\u043d\u043a\u0438_\u041a\u0443\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044b</ref> in [[Minsk]].\n\n===In Vilnius and St. Petersburg===\nKupala moved to [[Vilnius]] in 1908, where he continued with his career as a poet. The same year the first published collection of his poems, ''\u0416\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0439\u043a\u0430'' (''The Little Flute'') brought on the ire of the czarist government, which ordered the book confiscated as an anti-government publication. The order for Kupala's arrest was revoked in 1909, but a second printing was again confiscated, this time by the local authorities in Vilnius. Kupala ceased working for the ''[[Nasha Niva]]'' in order to avoid ruining the reputation of the newspaper.\n\nKupala left for [[Saint Petersburg]] in 1909. The subsequent year saw the publication of several works, including the poem ''\u0410\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0441\u044c\u043d\u044f'' (''Eternal Song''), which appeared as a book in St. Petersburg in July 1910. ''\u0421\u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0435'' (''Dream on a Barrow'')\u2013 completed in August 1910 \u2013symbolised the poor state of Kupala's Belarusian homeland. Kupala left St. Petersburg and returned to Vilnius in 1913. Among those influencing Kupala in the 1910s was [[Maxim Gorky]].\n\n===During the Soviet period===\nKupala's writing changed to an optimistic tone following the [[October Revolution|Great October Revolution]] of 1917. Among Kupala's numerous translations into the Belarusian language were the internationalist-Marxist anthem ''[[The Internationale]]'' and an ancient epic poem [[The Tale of Igor's Campaign]] (translated in 1921).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myslenedrevo.com.ua/en/Lit/S/SlovoPolkIgor.html|title=The tale of Igor's campaign}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rg.ru/2011/11/03/slovo.html|title=\u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c 90 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0443 \"\u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043a\u0443 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0435\" \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a|author=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0442|publisher= \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|trans-title=the first translation of The Tale of Igor's Campaign into Belarusian was made 90 years ago|language=Russian}}</ref> Nevertheless, Kupala maintained his connections with the [[Anti-Sovietism|anti-Soviet]] oriented nationalist emigres of the [[Belarusian People's Republic]], who exhorted that he join them in exile in [[Czechoslovakia]] during a trip abroad in 1927. At home, the newly established authorities considered him with some distrust\u2013at times, criticism of Kupala in the press mounted insofar as Kupala's activities were regarded as too oriented around nationalism. This period stopped once Kupala printed a public letter of apology in the 1930s.{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\nKupala was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]] in 1941 for the poetry collection ''\u0410\u0434 \u0441\u044d\u0440\u0446\u0430'' (''From the Heart''). With the [[Occupation of Belarus by Nazi Germany]] in 1941, because of being very ill he moved to Moscow and then to [[Tatarstan]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} Even from there he wrote poems supporting the [[Soviet partisans#Belarus|Belarusian partisans]] fighting against [[Nazi Germany]]. He died in Moscow in 1942, aged 59, having fallen down the stairwell in [[Hotel Moskva (Moscow)|Hotel Moskva]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} \n \n==Legacy==\n[[File:Yanka Kupala monument in Ashdod - 2.jpg|thumb|A monument to Yanka Kupala in Ashdod, Israel]]\nKupala became recognised as a symbol of [[culture of Belarus]] during the Soviet era. A museum, organised in [[Minsk]] through the efforts of his widow in 1945, is the leading literary museum in Belarus. [[Hrodna State University]] was named after Yanka Kupala. There is also a [[Yanka Kupala Park|park]] named after him with a monument to the poet, a [[Yanka Kupala National Academic Theatre|theatre]] and a [[Minsk Metro|metro]] station ([[Kupala\u016dskaja (Minsk Metro)|Kupala\u016dskaja]]) named after him in [[Minsk]].\n\nAt the Arrow Park in [[Monroe, New York]] there is a monument of Yanka Kupala that was created by Belarusian sculptor Anatoly Anikeichik and architect Sergey Botkovsky. Since 1973 it is presented to the American Side.<ref>[http://un.mfa.gov.by/en/mission/news/df5a48b73098f554.html Flowers laid at Yanka Kupala monument in Arrow Park, Monroe, New York]</ref> A monument to Kupala is placed on a square in the city of [[Ashdod]] in [[Israel]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Yanka Kupala}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120316175729/http://old.knihi.com/kupala/sanety-eng.html   Janka Kupala's sonnets] translated by [[Vera Rich]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kupala, Janka}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Maladzyechna District]]\n[[Category:People from Minsky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme Soviet of the Byelorussian SSR (1938\u20131946)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belarusian poets]]\n[[Category:Belarusian writers]]\n[[Category:Soviet poets]]\n[[Category:Soviet male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian-language writers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian male poets]]\n[[Category:Socialist realism writers]]\n[[Category:Stalin Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = J\u00e1nka Kup\u00e1la<br>\u042f\u0301\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0430\n| image       = Yanka Kupala.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{OldStyleDate|July 7|1882|June 25}} \n| birth_place = [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], [[Minsk Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date  = June 28, 1942 (aged 59)\n| death_place = Moscow, [[Soviet Union]]\n| occupation  = Poet and writer\n| nationality = Belarusian\n| period      = 1903\u20131942\n}}\n\n'''Yanka Kupala''' (also spelled '''J\u00e1nka Kup\u00e1la''' or '''Janka Kupa\u0142a''', {{lang-be|\u042f\u0301\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u043f\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0430}}; {{OldStyleDate|July 7|1882|June 25}} \u2013 June 28, 1942) \u2013 was the [[pen name]] of '''Iv\u00e1n Damin\u00edkavich Luts\u00e9vich''' (''Ivan Daminikavi\u010d \u0141ucevi\u010d'', {{lang-be|\u0406\u0432\u0430\u0301\u043d \u0414\u0430\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0301\u043a\u0430\u0432\u0456\u0447 \u041b\u0443\u0446\u044d\u0301\u0432\u0456\u0447}}), a [[Belarus]]ian poet and writer. Kupala is considered one of the greatest Belarusian-language writers of the 20th century.\n\n==Biography==\n{{unsourced|section|date=February 2017}}\n===Early life===\n[[Image:Yanka Kupala's House.JPG|thumb|left|House where Janka Kupala was born ([[folwark]] [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], [[Minsk district]], Belarus)]]\n[[Image:Yanka Kupala in Saint Petersburg, 1909.jpg|thumb|left|Janka Kupala during his study under professor A. Charniaev in [[Saint Petersburg]], 1909]]\nKupala was born on July 7, 1882 in [[Maladzyechna Raion|Viazynka]], a [[folwark]] settlement near [[Maladzyechna]]. His family was noble, although both of Kupala's parents were employed as tenant farmers at the folwark. Kupala was thus essentially born into a landless peasant class. Kupala received a traditional Belarusian education, completing his studies in 1898. Following the death of his father in 1902, Kupala worked a variety of short-term jobs, including as a tutor, a shop assistant, and a record keeper.\n\nKupala's first serious literary attempt was ''Ziarno'', a Polish-language sentimental poem which he completed around 1903\u20131904 under the pseudonym \"K-a.\" His first Belarusian-language work (\"\u041c\u0430\u044f \u0434\u043e\u043b\u044f\") was dated July 15, 1904. Kupala's first published poem, \"\u041c\u0443\u0436\u044b\u043a\" (\"Peasant\"), was published approximately a year later, appearing in Belarusian in the Russophone Belarusian newspaper ''Severo-Zapadnyi Krai'' (''Northwestern [[Krai]]'') on May 11, 1905. A number of subsequent poems by Kupala appeared in the Belarusian-language newspaper ''[[Nasha Niva]]'' from 1906 to 1907.<ref>[http://archives.gov.by/eng/index.php?id=951386 Yanka Kupala: personality and work]</ref>\n\n===In Vilnius and St. Petersburg===\nKupala moved to [[Vilnius]] in 1908, where he continued with his career as a poet. The same year the first published collection of his poems, ''\u0416\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0439\u043a\u0430'' (''The Little Flute'') brought on the ire of the czarist government, which ordered the book confiscated as an anti-government publication. The order for Kupala's arrest was revoked in 1909, but a second printing was again confiscated, this time by the local authorities in Vilnius. Kupala ceased working for the ''[[Nasha Niva]]'' in order to avoid ruining the reputation of the newspaper.\n\nKupala left for [[Saint Petersburg]] in 1909. The subsequent year saw the publication of several works, including the poem ''\u0410\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0441\u044c\u043d\u044f'' (''Eternal Song''), which appeared as a book in St. Petersburg in July 1910. ''\u0421\u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0435'' (''Dream on a Barrow'')\u2013 completed in August 1910 \u2013symbolised the poor state of Kupala's Belarusian homeland. Kupala left St. Petersburg and returned to Vilnius in 1913. Among those influencing Kupala in the 1910s was [[Maxim Gorky]].\n\n===During the Soviet period===\nKupala's writing changed to an optimistic tone following the [[October Revolution|Great October Revolution]] of 1917. Among Kupala's numerous translations into the Belarusian language were the internationalist-Marxist anthem ''[[The Internationale]]'' and an ancient epic poem [[The Tale of Igor's Campaign]] (translated in 1921).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myslenedrevo.com.ua/en/Lit/S/SlovoPolkIgor.html|title=The tale of Igor's campaign}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rg.ru/2011/11/03/slovo.html|title=\u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c 90 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0443 \"\u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043a\u0443 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0435\" \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a|author=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0442|publisher= \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430|trans-title=the first translation of The Tale of Igor's Campaign into Belarusian was made 90 years ago|language=Russian}}</ref> Nevertheless, Kupala maintained his connections with the [[Anti-Sovietism|anti-Soviet]] oriented nationalist emigres of the [[Belarusian People's Republic]], who exhorted that he join them in exile in [[Czechoslovakia]] during a trip abroad in 1927. At home, the newly established authorities considered him with some distrust\u2013at times, criticism of Kupala in the press mounted insofar as Kupala's activities were regarded as too oriented around nationalism. This period stopped once Kupala printed a public letter of apology in the 1930s.{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\nKupala was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]] in 1941 for the poetry collection ''\u0410\u0434 \u0441\u044d\u0440\u0446\u0430'' (''From the Heart''). With the [[Occupation of Belarus by Nazi Germany]] in 1941, because of being very ill he moved to Moscow and then to [[Tatarstan]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} Even from there he wrote poems supporting the [[Soviet partisans#Belarus|Belarusian partisans]] fighting against [[Nazi Germany]]. He died in Moscow in 1942, aged 59, having fallen down the stairwell in [[Hotel Moskva (Moscow)|Hotel Moskva]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} \n \n==Legacy==\n[[File:Yanka Kupala monument in Ashdod - 2.jpg|thumb|A monument to Yanka Kupala in Ashdod, Israel]]\nKupala became recognised as a symbol of [[culture of Belarus]] during the Soviet era. A museum, organised in [[Minsk]] through the efforts of his widow in 1945, is the leading literary museum in Belarus. [[Hrodna State University]] was named after Yanka Kupala. There is also a [[Yanka Kupala Park|park]] named after him with a monument to the poet, a [[Yanka Kupala National Academic Theatre|theatre]] and a [[Minsk Metro|metro]] station ([[Kupala\u016dskaja (Minsk Metro)|Kupala\u016dskaja]]) named after him in [[Minsk]].\n\nAt the Arrow Park in [[Monroe, New York]] there is a monument of Yanka Kupala that was created by Belarusian sculptor Anatoly Anikeichik and architect Sergey Botkovsky. Since 1973 it is presented to the American Side.<ref>[http://un.mfa.gov.by/en/mission/news/df5a48b73098f554.html Flowers laid at Yanka Kupala monument in Arrow Park, Monroe, New York]</ref> A monument to Kupala is placed on a square in the city of [[Ashdod]] in [[Israel]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Yanka Kupala}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120316175729/http://old.knihi.com/kupala/sanety-eng.html   Janka Kupala's sonnets] translated by [[Vera Rich]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kupala, Janka}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Maladzyechna District]]\n[[Category:People from Minsky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme Soviet of the Byelorussian SSR (1938\u20131946)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belarusian poets]]\n[[Category:Belarusian writers]]\n[[Category:Soviet poets]]\n[[Category:Soviet male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian-language writers]]\n[[Category:Belarusian male poets]]\n[[Category:Socialist realism writers]]\n[[Category:Stalin Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "added personal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yanka_Kupala"}
{"title_page": "Cecidomyiinae", "text_new": "{{short description|Subfamily of flies}}\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Hessian Fly.jpg\n| image_caption = The [[Hessian fly]] (''Mayetiola destructor'') from the subfamily Cecidomyiinae\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Fly|Diptera]]\n| superfamilia = [[Sciaroidea]]\n| familia = [[Cecidomyiidae]]\n| subfamilia = '''Cecidomyiinae'''\n| subdivision_ranks = Supertribes\n| subdivision = *[[Asphondyliidi]]\n*[[Cecidomyiidi]]\n*[[Lasiopteridi]]\n| synonyms =\n}}\n[[File:Asphondylia solidaginis side view.jpg|thumb|''Asphondylia solidaginis'']]\n[[File:Rhopalomyia solidaginis adult.jpg|thumb|''Rhopalomyia solidaginis'']]\n[[File:Vitisiella larva.jpg|thumb|''[[Vitisiella]]'' larva]]\n[[File:Dasineura pellex galls leaf.jpg|thumb|Galls of ''[[Dasineura pellex]]'' on leaf of ash tree (''[[Fraxinus]]'')]]\n\nThe '''Cecidomyiinae'''  are a  [[Family (biology)|subfamily]] of flies often called '''gall midges''' or '''gall gnats'''.\n \n==Systematics==\nCecidomyiinae - supertribes, tribes, and genera:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skuhrav\u00e1|first=Marcela|date=2006-01-01|title=Species richness of gall midges (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae) in the main biogeographical regions of the world|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292070637_Species_richness_of_gall_midges_Diptera_Cecidomyiidae_in_the_main_biogeographical_regions_of_the_world|journal=Acta Societatis Zoologicae Bohemicae|volume=69|pages=327\u2013372}}</ref>\n\n*Supertribe [[Asphondyliidi]]\n**Tribe [[Asphondyliini]]\n***''[[Asphondylia]]'' <small>[[Hermann Loew|Loew]], 1850</small>\n**Tribe [[Kiefferiini]]\n***''[[Kiefferia]]''  <small>[[Josef Mik|Mik]], 1895</small>\n**Tribe [[Polystephini]]\n***''[[Polystepha]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1897</small>\n**Tribe [[Schizomyiini]]\n***''[[Placochela]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1916</small>\n***''[[Schizomyia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1889</small>\n*Supertribe [[Cecidomyiidi]]\n**Tribe [[Anadiplosini]]\n**Tribe [[Aphidoletini]]\n**Tribe [[Cecidomyiini]]\n***''[[Acodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1895</small>\n***''[[Ametrodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Anabremia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Anisostephus]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1917</small>\n***''[[Antichiridium]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1911</small>\n***''[[Aphidoletes]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1904</small>\n***''[[Arthrocnodax]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1895</small>\n***''[[Atrichosema]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1904</small>\n***''[[Blastodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Camptodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Cecidomyia]]'' <small>[[Johann Fischer von Waldheim|Fischer von Waldheim]]\\n[[Johann Wilhelm Meigen|Meigen]], 1803</small>\n***''[[Clinodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1894</small>\n***''[[Contarinia]]'' <small>[[Camillo R\u00f3ndani|R\u00f3ndani]], 1860</small>\n***''[[Coquillettomyia]]'' <small>[[Ephraim Porter Felt|Felt]], 1908</small>\n***''[[Dichodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Diodaulus]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1917</small>\n***''[[Drisina]]'' <small>Giard, 1893</small>\n***''[[Endaphis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1896</small>\n***''[[Endopsylla]]'' <small>de Meijere, 1907</small>\n***''[[Feltiella]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Geodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1909</small>\n***''[[Giardomyia]]'' <small>[[Ephraim Porter Felt|Felt]], 1908</small>\n***''[[Hadrobremia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Haplodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Harmandiola]]'' <small>Skuhrav\u00e1, 1997</small>\n***''[[Hygrodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Lestodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1894</small>\n***''[[Loewiola]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1896</small>\n***''[[Macrodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1895</small>\n***''[[Mamaevia]]'' <small>Skuhrav\u00e1, 1967</small>\n***''[[Massalongia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1897</small>\n***''[[Monarthropalpus]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1892</small>\n***''[[Monobremia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Monodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Mycocecis]]'' <small>[[Frederick Wallace Edwards|Edwards]], 1922</small>\n***''[[Mycodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1895</small>\n***''[[Myricomyia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1900</small>\n***''[[Octodiplosis]]'' <small>Giard, 1894</small>\n***''[[Parallelodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1910</small>\n***''[[Planetella]]'' <small>Westwood, 1840</small>\n***''[[Plemeliella]]'' <small>Seitner, 1908</small>\n***''[[Putoniella]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1896</small>\n***''[[Resseliella]]'' <small>Seitner, 1906</small>\n***''[[Silvestriola]]'' <small>Skuhrav\u00e1, 1997</small>\n***''[[Sitodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</small>\n***''[[Stenodiplosis]]'' <small>Reuter, 1895</small>\n***''[[Thecodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1895</small>\n***''[[Tricholaba]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1917</small>\n***''[[Xenodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Ephraim Porter Felt|Felt]], 1911</small>\n***''[[Xylodiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1894</small>\n***''[[Zeuxidiplosis]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1904</small>\n**Tribe [[Centrodiplosini]]\n**Tribe [[Clinodiplosini]]\n***''[[Schismatodiplosis]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1916</small>\n*Supertribe [[Lasiopteridi]]\n**Tribe [[Alycaulini]] <ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf| title=A Catalog of Cecidomyiidae of the World. 4th Edition| last1=Gagn\u00e9| first1=R.J.| last2=Jaschhof| first2=M.| date=2017}}</ref>\n*** ''[[Alycaulus]]''\n*** ''[[Asteromyia]]''\n*** ''[[Astictoneura]]''\n*** ''[[Atolasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Baccharomyia]]''\n*** ''[[Brachylasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Calamomyia]]''\n*** ''[[Chilophaga]]''\n*** ''[[Couridiplosis]]''\n*** ''[[Edestochilus]]''\n*** ''[[Edestosperma]]''\n*** ''[[Epilasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Geraldesia]]''\n*** ''[[Lobolasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Marilasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Meunieriella]]''\n*** ''[[Neolasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Protaplonyx]]''\n*** ''[[Smilasioptera]]''\n*** ''[[Xipholasioptera]]''\n**Tribe [[Brachineurini]]\n***''[[Brachineura]]'' <small>[[Camillo R\u00f3ndani|R\u00f3ndani]], 1840</small>\n***''[[Brachyneurina]]'' <small>Mamaev, 1967</small>\n***''[[Mikiola]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1912</small>\n***''[[Prolauthia]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1915</small>\n**Tribe [[Lasiopterini]]\n***''[[Baldratia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1897</small>\n***''[[Hybolasioptera]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1915</small>\n***''[[Lasioptera]]'' <small>[[Johann Fischer von Waldheim|Fischer von Waldheim]]\\n[[Johann Wilhelm Meigen|Meigen]], 1818</small>\n***''[[Ozirhincus]]'' <small>[[Camillo R\u00f3ndani|R\u00f3ndani]], 1840</small>\n***''[[Stefaniella]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1898</small>\n**Tribe [[Ledomyiini]]\n***''[[Ledomyia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1895</small>\n**Tribe [[Oligotrophini]]\n***''[[Amerhapha]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1914</small>\n***''[[Arceuthomyia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</small>\n***''[[Arnoldiola]]'' <small>Strand, 1926</small>\n***''[[Bayeriola]]'' <small>Gagn\u00e9, 1991</small>\n***''[[Blastomyia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</small>\n***''[[Bremiola]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1915</small>\n***''[[Craneiobia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</sma