small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1914</small>\n***''[[Psectrosema]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1904</small>\n***''[[Rabdophaga]]'' <small>[[John Obadiah Westwood|Westwood]], 1847</small>\n***''[[Rhopalomyia]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1892</small>\n***''[[Rondaniola]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen & Hedicke, 1938</small>\n***''[[Sackenomyia]]'' <small>[[Ephraim Porter Felt|Felt]], 1908</small>\n***''[[Schmidtiella]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1914</small>\n***''[[Semudobia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</small>\n***''[[Spurgia]]'' <small>Gagn\u00e9, 1990</small>\n***''[[Taxomyia]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1912</small>\n***''[[Trotteria]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1901</small>\n***''[[Wachtliella]]'' <small>R\u00fcbsaamen, 1915</small>\n***''[[Zygiobia]]'' <small>[[Jean-Jacques Kieffer|Kieffer]], 1913</small>\n{{Expand list|date=February 2011}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Cecidomyiinae genera]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q766680}}\n\n[[Category:Cecidomyiinae| ]]\n[[Category:Nematocera families]]\n", "name_user": "Dyanega", "label": "safe", "comment": "rv inappropriate category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecidomyiinae"}
{"title_page": "Howard Gardner", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|image=Howard Gardner.jpg\n|image_size= 150px\n|birth_name = Howard Earl Gardner\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1943|7|11|mf=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date =\n|death_place= \n|nationality= American\n|field= [[Psychology]], [[education]]\n|work_institution= [[Harvard University]]\n|alma_mater = [[Harvard College]]\n|doctoral_advisor=\n|influences= [[Jean Piaget]], [[Jerome Bruner]], [[Nelson Goodman]]<ref name=ew>{{cite web |last=Winner |first=Ellen |title=The History of Howard Raboloco Gardner |url=http://www.howardgardner.com/bio/lerner_winner.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629200840/http://www.howardgardner.com/bio/lerner_winner.htm |archivedate=2007-06-29 }}</ref>\n|influenced=\n|known_for = [[Theory of multiple intelligences]]\n|website={{URL|www.howardgardner.com/}}\n|spouse=[[Ellen Winner]]\n}}\n{{Psychology sidebar}}\n\n'''Howard Earl Gardner''' (born July 11, 1943) is an American [[developmental psychologist]] and the John H. and Elisabeth A. Hobbs Research Professor of Cognition and Education at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] at [[Harvard University]]. He is currently the senior director of Harvard Project Zero, and since 1995, he has been the co-director of The Good Project.<ref name=\"Gordon, Lynn Melby 2006\">Gordon, Lynn Melby. \"Gardner, Howard (1943\u2013).\" Encyclopedia of Human Development. Ed. Neil J. Salkind. Vol. 2. Thousand Oaks, CA: SAGE Reference, 2006. 552-553. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 27 Oct. 2014.</ref>\n\nGardner has written hundreds of research articles<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\" /> and thirty books that have been translated into more than thirty languages.  He is best known for his [[theory of multiple intelligences]], as outlined in his 1983 book ''Frames of Mind: The Theory of Multiple Intelligences''.<ref name=\"Gordon, Lynn Melby 2006\"/>\n\nGardner retired from teaching in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/19/05/tribute-howard-gardner}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHoward Earl Gardner was born July 11, 1943, in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], to Ralph Gardner and Hilde (n\u00e9e Weilheimer) Gardner, German-Jewish immigrants who fled Germany prior to [[World War II]].<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Anderman |editor-first1=Eric|editor-last2=Anderman |editor-first2=Lynley |title=Psychology of Classroom Learning: An Encyclopedia |date=2009 |publisher=Macmillan Reference |location=Detroit, USA |pages=423\u2013425 |volume=1 |url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?sgHitCountType=None&sort=RELEVANCE&inPS=true&prodId=GVRL&userGroupName=cuny_hunter&tabID=T003&searchId=R1&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&contentSegment=&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=5&contentSet=GALE%7cCX3027800122&&docId=GALE%7cCX3027800122&docType=GALE |accessdate=28 Dec 2014}} a part of the Gale Virtual Reference Library.</ref>\n\nGardner described himself as \"a studious child who gained much pleasure from playing the piano\".<ref name=ZeroBio /> Although Gardner never became a professional pianist, he taught piano from 1958 to 1969.<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\">{{cite book |last=Doorey |first=Marie |editors=Bonnie R. Strickland, executive editor |title=Gardner, Howard Earl |work=The Gale Encyclopedia of Psychology |date=2001 |publisher=Gale Group |location=Detroit, MI |isbn=978-0-7876-4786-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/galeencyclopedia00bonn/page/272 272\u2013273, 699] |edition=2nd |url=https://archive.org/details/galeencyclopedia00bonn/page/272 |accessdate=2014-12-07 }} a part of the Gale Virtual Reference Library.</ref>\n\nEducation was of the utmost importance in the Gardner home. While his parents had hoped that he would attend [[Phillips Academy Andover]] in Massachusetts, Gardner opted to attend a school closer to his hometown in Pennsylvania, [[Wyoming Seminary]].  Gardner had a desire to learn and greatly excelled in school.<ref>Webber, Jacob. \"Gardner, Howard.\" Encyclopedia of the History of Psychological Theories. Ed. Robert W. Rieber. Vol. 1. New York: Springer, 2012. 464-465. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 10 Dec. 2014.</ref>\n\n===Career===\nGardner graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1965 with an [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in social relations, and studied under the renowned [[Erik Erikson]]. After earning a Master\u2019s degree at the London School of Economics, he would go on to obtain his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[developmental psychology]] at Harvard while working with psychologists [[Roger Brown (psychologist)|Roger Brown]] and [[Jerome Bruner]], and philosopher [[Nelson Goodman]].<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\" />\n\nFor his postdoctoral fellowship, Gardner worked alongside [[Norman Geschwind]] at Boston Veterans Administration Hospital and continued his work there for another 20 years.<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\"/> Gardner began teaching at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] in 1986. Since 1995, much of the focus of his work has been on The GoodWork Project, now part of a larger initiative known as The Good Project that encourages excellence, ethics, and engagement in work, digital life, and beyond.\n\nIn 2000, Gardner, [[Kurt W. Fischer|Kurt Fischer]], and their colleagues at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] established the master's degree program in Mind, Brain and Education. This program was thought to be the first of its kind around the world. Many universities in both the United States and abroad have since developed similar programs. Four years later in 2004, Gardner would continue writing about the mind and brain and would publish ''Changing Minds: The Art and Science of Changing Our Own and Other People's Minds'', a book about seven forms of mind-change.<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\"/>\n\nGardner retired from teaching in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/19/05/tribute-howard-gardner}}</ref>\n\n===Theory and criticism===\nAccording to Gardner's [[theory of multiple intelligences]], humans have several different ways of processing information, and these ways are relatively independent of one another. The theory is a critique of the standard intelligence theory, which emphasizes the correlation among abilities, as well as traditional measures like IQ tests that typically only account for linguistic, logical, and spatial abilities. Since 1999, Gardner has identified eight intelligences: linguistic, logical-mathematical, musical, spatial, bodily/kinesthetic, interpersonal, intrapersonal, and naturalistic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Multiple Intelligences Theory|url=https://smiletutor.sg/how-to-harness-develop-your-natural-strengths-multiple-intelligences-theory/|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Gardner and colleagues have also considered two additional intelligences, existential and pedagogical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://howardgardner01.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/473-madrid-oct-22-2011.pdf|title=The Theory of Multiple Intelligences: As Psychology, As Education, As Social Science Howard Gardner|work=Howardgardner01.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multipleintelligencesoasis.org|title=Home - Mi Oasis|work=Mi Oasis|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> Many teachers, school administrators, and special educators have been inspired by Gardner's theory of multiple intelligences as it has allowed for the idea that there is more than one way to define a person's intellect.<ref>Gordon, Lynn Melby. \"Gardner, Howard (1943\u2013).\" Encyclopedia of Human Development. Ed. Neil J. Salkind. Vol. 2. Thousand Oaks, CA: SAGE Reference, 2006. 552-553. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 8 Dec. 2014.</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Tutor City|url=https://tutorcity.sgaccessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> \nGardner's definition of intelligence has been met with some criticism in education circles<ref>http://educationnext.org/reframing-the-mind/</ref> as well as in the field of psychology.  Perhaps the strongest and most enduring critique of his theory of multiple intelligences centers on its lack of empirical evidence, much of which points to a single construct of intelligence called \"g\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Klein | first1 = Perry D | year = 1998 | title = A Response to Howard Gardner: Falsifiability, Empirical Evidence, and Pedagogical Usefulness in Educational Psychologies | url = | journal = Canadian Journal of Education | volume = 23 | issue = 1| pages = 103\u2013112 | doi = 10.2307/1585969 | jstor = 1585969 }}</ref> Gardner responds that his theory is based entirely on applied evidence as opposed to experimental evidence, as he does not believe experimental evidence is appropriate for a theoretical synthesis.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gardner | first1 = Howard | year = 2006| title = On failing to grasp the core of MI theory: A response to Visser et al. | url = | journal = Intelligence | volume = 34 | issue = 5| pages = 503\u2013505 | doi = 10.1016/j.intell.2006.04.002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gardner | first1 = Howard | last2 = Moran | first2 = Seana | year = 2006| title = The science of multiple intelligences theory: A response to Lynn Waterhouse | url = | journal = Educational Psychologist | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 227\u2013232 | doi = 10.1207/s15326985ep4104_2 }}</ref>\n\nGardner's theory of multiple intelligences can be seen as both a departure from and a continuation of the last century's work on the subject of human intelligence.  Other prominent psychologists whose contributions variously developed or expanded the field of study include [[Charles Spearman]], [[Louis Thurstone]], [[Edward Thorndike]], and [[Robert Sternberg]].\n\nIn 1967, Professor [[Nelson Goodman]] started an educational program called Project Zero at the Harvard Graduate School of Education, which began with a focus in arts education and now spans throughout a wide variety of educational arenas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pz.harvard.edu/history.php|title=Project Zero: History|work=Pz.harvard.edu|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014215717/http://www.pz.harvard.edu/history.php|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Howard Gardner and David Perkins were founding Research Assistants and later Co-Directed Project Zero from 1972-2000. Project Zero's mission is to understand and enhance learning, thinking, and creativity in the arts, as well as humanistic and scientific disciplines at the individual and institutional levels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tutor City|url=[[Tutor city|https://tutorcity.sg]]\n\n[[File:Goodworkteam.jpg|thumb|Goodworkteam|Good Project founders: [[William Damon]], [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]], and Gardner]]\n\nFor almost two decades, in collaboration with [[William Damon]], [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]], and several other colleagues, Gardner has been directing research at The Good Project on the nature of good work, good play, and good collaboration. The goal of his research is to determine what it means to achieve work that is at once excellent, engaging, and carried out in an ethical way. With colleagues Lynn Barendsen, Wendy Fischman, and Carrie James, Gardner has developed curricular toolkits on these topics for use in educational and professional circles.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Educating for Good Work: From Research to Practice| doi=10.1080/00071005.2013.829210|volume=61| issue=4|journal=British Journal of Educational Studies|pages=453\u2013470|year = 2013|last1 = Mucinskas|first1 = Daniel| last2=Gardner| first2=Howard| url=https://www.issuelab.org/permalink/resource/20502}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements and awards==\nIn 1981 Gardner was the recipient of a [[MacArthur Prize Fellowship]]. In 1990 he became the first American to receive the [[University of Louisville]] [[Grawemeyer Award]] in Education.<ref name=grawemeyer.org>{{cite web |title=1990 - Howard Gardner |url=http://grawemeyer.org/education/previous-winners/1990-howard-gardner.html |work=Grawemeyer.org |accessdate=11 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014072135/http://grawemeyer.org/education/previous-winners/1990-howard-gardner.html |archive-date=14 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>   In 1985, The National Psychology Awards for Excellence in the Media, awarded Gardner The Book Award for ''Frames of Mind: The Theory of Multiple Intelligences'', which was published by Basic Books.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eds.b.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?sid=f5a31b19-82de-4d07-b703-f3d90a7580e3%40sessionmgr112&vid=15&hid=126/ |title=National psychology awards for excellence in the media. |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>  In 1987, he received the William James Award from the [[American Psychological Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/en/press/news/howard-gardner-2011-prince-of-asturias-award-for-social-sciences/ |title=Howard Gardner, 2011 Prince of Asturias Award for Social Sciences - The Prince of Asturias Foundation |work=Fpa.es |date= |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref> In 2000 he received a fellowship from the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|John S. Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]].  Four years later he was named an Honorary Professor at [[East China Normal University]] in Shanghai. In the years 2005 and 2008 he was selected by [[Foreign Policy]] and [[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]] magazines as one of the top 100 most influential public intellectuals in the world.<ref name=\"Fpa.es\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/en/press/news/howard-gardner-2011-prince-of-asturias-award-for-social-sciences/ |title=Howard Gardner, 2011 Prince of Asturias Award for Social Sciences - The Prince of Asturias Foundation |work=Fpa.es |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> In 2011, he won the [[Prince of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]] in Social Sciences for his development of multiple intelligences theory.<ref name=\"Fpa.es\"/> In 2015, he received the Brock International Prize in Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brockprize.org/laureates2 |title=Brock International Prize in Education Laureates |work=BrockPrize.org |date= |accessdate=2017-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017032840/http://brockprize.org/laureates2 |archive-date=2016-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe has received 31 honorary degrees from colleges and universities around the world, including institutions in Bulgaria, Canada, Chile, Greece, Hong Kong, Ireland, Israel, Italy, South Korea, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pz.harvard.edu/pis/hg.htm |title=Howard Gardner |work=Pz.harvard.edu |accessdate=2012-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815073200/http://www.pz.harvard.edu/PIs/HG.htm |archivedate=2012-08-15 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHoward Gardner is married to Ellen Winner, Professor of Psychology at Boston College. They have one child, Benjamin. Gardner has three children from an earlier marriage: Kerith (1969), Jay (1971), and Andrew (1976); and five grandchildren: Oscar (2005), Agnes (2011), Olivia (2015), Faye Marguerite (2016), and August Pierre (2019).<ref name=ZeroBio>{{cite web |title=Howard Gardner Project Zero Biography |url=http://pz.harvard.edu/who-we-are/people/howard-gardner|work=Pz.harvard.edu|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Multiple Intelligences Reconsidered |editor-last=Kincheloe |editor-first=Joe L. <!--|author=Joe L. Kincheloe|author2=Kathleen Nolan|author3=Yusef Progler|author4=Peter Appelbaum|author5=Richard Cary|author6=Donald S. Blumenthal-Jones|author7=Marla Morris|author8=Jay L. Lemke|author9=Gaile S. Cannella|author10=Danny Weil|author11=Kathleen S. Berry--> |year=2004 |publisher=Peter Lang |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8204-7098-6 |series=Counterpoints v. 278 |issn=1058-1634 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/multipleintellig0000unse_o8g0 }}\n* {{cite book |title=\"A Blessing of Influences\" in Howard Gardner Under Fire |editor-last=Schaler |editor-first=Jeffrey A. |author=Howard Gardner |year=2006 |publisher=Open Court |location=Illinois |isbn=978-0-8126-9604-2}}\n* {{cite book |title=To Open Minds: Chinese Clues to the Dilemma of American Education |author=Howard Gardner |year=1989 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-465-08629-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/toopenminds00howa }}\n* {{cite book |title=Making learning visible |author1=Howard Gardner |author2=Vea Vecchi |author3=Carla Rinaldi |author4=Paola Cagliari |year=2011 |publisher=Reggio Children |location=Italy |isbn=978-88-87960-67-9}}\n* {{cite book |title=\"Howard Gardner\" in Fifty Modern Thinkers in Education |editor-last=Palmer |editor-first=Joy |author=M. Kornhaber |year=2001 |publisher=Routledge |location=New York |isbn=978-0415224086 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/fiftymodernthink0000unse }}\n* {{cite book |title=\"Howard Gardner, Frames of Mind\" in 50 Psychology Classics |author=Tom Butler-Bowdon |year=2007 |publisher=Nicholas Brealey |location=London & Boston |isbn=978-1-85788-386-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/50psychologyclas0000butl }}\n* Gordon, L. M. (2006). Howard Gardner. \"The encyclopedia of human development.\" Thousand Oaks: Sage Publications, 2, 552-553.\n* {{cite book|last=Gardner|first=Howard|title=Truth, beauty, and goodness reframed: Educating for the virtues in the 21st century|year=2011|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York}}\n* {{cite book |title=The App Generation: How Today's Youth Navigate Identity, Intimacy, and Imagination in a Digital World|author1=Gardner, H.  |author2=Davis, K.|year=2013|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300196214}}\n* {{cite book |title=From the Ivory Tower to the Schoolhouse: How Scholarship Becomes Common Knowledge in Education|author=Schneider, Jack|year=2014|publisher=Harvard Education Press|isbn=978-1612506692}}\n* {{cite book |title=[https://howardgardner01.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/festschrift-_-volumes-1-2-_-final.pdf Mind, Work, and Life]: A Festschrift on the Occasion of Howard Gardner's 70th Birthday|author=Gardner, Howard|year=2014|publisher=Create Space|isbn=978-1499381702}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Howard Gardner}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.thegoodproject.org/  The Good Project]\n*[http://www.howardgardner.com/ The Official Howard Gardner Website]\n*[http://www.multipleintelligencesoasis.org/ The Official Website of Multiple Intelligences Theory]\n*[http://www.twitter.com/DrHowardGardner/ Howard Gardner Twitter]\n*[http://www.pz.harvard.edu/ Project Zero]\n*[http://www.gse.harvard.edu/directory/faculty/faculty-detail/?fc=316&flt=g&sub=all Faculty Profile] \u2014 [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] website\n*{{C-SPAN|Howard Gardner}}\n\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Social Sciences}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, Howard}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American business theorists]]\n[[Category:American educational theorists]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:Creativity researchers]]\n[[Category:Developmental psychologists]]\n[[Category:Educational psychologists]]\n[[Category:Intelligence researchers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:New York University faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Wyoming Seminary alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|image=Howard Gardner.jpg\n|image_size= 150px\n|birth_name = Howard Earl Gardner\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1943|7|11|mf=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n|death_date =\n|death_place= \n|nationality= American\n|field= [[Psychology]], [[education]]\n|work_institution= [[Harvard University]]\n|alma_mater = [[Harvard College]]\n|doctoral_advisor=\n|influences= [[Jean Piaget]], [[Jerome Bruner]], [[Nelson Goodman]]<ref name=ew>{{cite web |last=Winner |first=Ellen |title=The History of Howard Raboloco Gardner |url=http://www.howardgardner.com/bio/lerner_winner.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629200840/http://www.howardgardner.com/bio/lerner_winner.htm |archivedate=2007-06-29 }}</ref>\n|influenced=\n|known_for = [[Theory of multiple intelligences]]\n|website={{URL|www.howardgardner.com/}}\n|spouse=[[Ellen Winner]]\n}}\n{{Psychology sidebar}}\n\n'''Howard Earl Gardner''' (born July 11, 1943) is an American [[developmental psychologist]] and the John H. and Elisabeth A. Hobbs Research Professor of Cognition and Education at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] at [[Harvard University]]. He is currently the senior director of Harvard Project Zero, and since 1995, he has been the co-director of The Good Project.<ref name=\"Gordon, Lynn Melby 2006\">Gordon, Lynn Melby. \"Gardner, Howard (1943\u2013).\" Encyclopedia of Human Development. Ed. Neil J. Salkind. Vol. 2. Thousand Oaks, CA: SAGE Reference, 2006. 552-553. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 27 Oct. 2014.</ref>\n\nGardner has written hundreds of research articles<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\" /> and thirty books that have been translated into more than thirty languages.  He is best known for his [[theory of multiple intelligences]], as outlined in his 1983 book ''Frames of Mind: The Theory of Multiple Intelligences''.<ref name=\"Gordon, Lynn Melby 2006\"/>\n\nGardner retired from teaching in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/19/05/tribute-howard-gardner}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHoward Earl Gardner was born July 11, 1943, in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], to Ralph Gardner and Hilde (n\u00e9e Weilheimer) Gardner, German-Jewish immigrants who fled Germany prior to [[World War II]].<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Anderman |editor-first1=Eric|editor-last2=Anderman |editor-first2=Lynley |title=Psychology of Classroom Learning: An Encyclopedia |date=2009 |publisher=Macmillan Reference |location=Detroit, USA |pages=423\u2013425 |volume=1 |url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?sgHitCountType=None&sort=RELEVANCE&inPS=true&prodId=GVRL&userGroupName=cuny_hunter&tabID=T003&searchId=R1&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&contentSegment=&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=5&contentSet=GALE%7cCX3027800122&&docId=GALE%7cCX3027800122&docType=GALE |accessdate=28 Dec 2014}} a part of the Gale Virtual Reference Library.</ref>\n\nGardner described himself as \"a studious child who gained much pleasure from playing the piano\".<ref name=ZeroBio /> Although Gardner never became a professional pianist, he taught piano from 1958 to 1969.<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\">{{cite book |last=Doorey |first=Marie |editors=Bonnie R. Strickland, executive editor |title=Gardner, Howard Earl |work=The Gale Encyclopedia of Psychology |date=2001 |publisher=Gale Group |location=Detroit, MI |isbn=978-0-7876-4786-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/galeencyclopedia00bonn/page/272 272\u2013273, 699] |edition=2nd |url=https://archive.org/details/galeencyclopedia00bonn/page/272 |accessdate=2014-12-07 }} a part of the Gale Virtual Reference Library.</ref>\n\nEducation was of the utmost importance in the Gardner home. While his parents had hoped that he would attend [[Phillips Academy Andover]] in Massachusetts, Gardner opted to attend a school closer to his hometown in Pennsylvania, [[Wyoming Seminary]].  Gardner had a desire to learn and greatly excelled in school.<ref>Webber, Jacob. \"Gardner, Howard.\" Encyclopedia of the History of Psychological Theories. Ed. Robert W. Rieber. Vol. 1. New York: Springer, 2012. 464-465. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 10 Dec. 2014.</ref>\n\n===Career===\nGardner graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1965 with an [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in social relations, and studied under the renowned [[Erik Erikson]]. After earning a Master\u2019s degree at the London School of Economics, he would go on to obtain his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[developmental psychology]] at Harvard while working with psychologists [[Roger Brown (psychologist)|Roger Brown]] and [[Jerome Bruner]], and philosopher [[Nelson Goodman]].<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\" />\n\nFor his postdoctoral fellowship, Gardner worked alongside [[Norman Geschwind]] at Boston Veterans Administration Hospital and continued his work there for another 20 years.<ref name=\"go.galegroup.com\"/> Gardner began teaching at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] in 1986. Since 1995, much of the focus of his work has been on The GoodWork Project, now part of a larger initiative known as The Good Project that encourages excellence, ethics, and engagement in work, digital life, and beyond.\n\nIn 2000, Gardner, [[Kurt W. Fischer|Kurt Fischer]], and their colleagues at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] established the master's degree program in Mind, Brain and Education. This program was thought to be the first of its kind around the world. Many universities in both the United States and abroad have since developed similar programs. Four years later in 2004, Gardner would continue writing about the mind and brain and would publish ''Changing Minds: The Art and Science of Changing Our Own and Other People's Minds'', a book about seven forms of mind-change.<ref name=\"CRLearnEnc\"/>\n\nGardner retired from teaching in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/19/05/tribute-howard-gardner}}</ref>\n\n===Theory and criticism===\nAccording to Gardner's [[theory of multiple intelligences]], humans have several different ways of processing information, and these ways are relatively independent of one another. The theory is a critique of the standard intelligence theory, which emphasizes the correlation among abilities, as well as traditional measures like IQ tests that typically only account for linguistic, logical, and spatial abilities. Since 1999, Gardner has identified eight intelligences: linguistic, logical-mathematical, musical, spatial, bodily/kinesthetic, interpersonal, intrapersonal, and naturalistic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Multiple Intelligences Theory|url=https://smiletutor.sg/how-to-harness-develop-your-natural-strengths-multiple-intelligences-theory/|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Gardner and colleagues have also considered two additional intelligences, existential and pedagogical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://howardgardner01.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/473-madrid-oct-22-2011.pdf|title=The Theory of Multiple Intelligences: As Psychology, As Education, As Social Science Howard Gardner|work=Howardgardner01.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multipleintelligencesoasis.org|title=Home - Mi Oasis|work=Mi Oasis|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> Many teachers, school administrators, and special educators have been inspired by Gardner's theory of multiple intelligences as it has allowed for the idea that there is more than one way to define a person's intellect.<ref>Gordon, Lynn Melby. \"Gardner, Howard (1943\u2013).\" Encyclopedia of Human Development. Ed. Neil J. Salkind. Vol. 2. Thousand Oaks, CA: SAGE Reference, 2006. 552-553. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. 8 Dec. 2014.</ref>\n\nGardner's definition of intelligence has been met with some criticism in education circles<ref>http://educationnext.org/reframing-the-mind/</ref> as well as in the field of psychology.  Perhaps the strongest and most enduring critique of his theory of multiple intelligences centers on its lack of empirical evidence, much of which points to a single construct of intelligence called \"g\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Klein | first1 = Perry D | year = 1998 | title = A Response to Howard Gardner: Falsifiability, Empirical Evidence, and Pedagogical Usefulness in Educational Psychologies | url = | journal = Canadian Journal of Education | volume = 23 | issue = 1| pages = 103\u2013112 | doi = 10.2307/1585969 | jstor = 1585969 }}</ref> Gardner responds that his theory is based entirely on applied evidence as opposed to experimental evidence, as he does not believe experimental evidence is appropriate for a theoretical synthesis.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gardner | first1 = Howard | year = 2006| title = On failing to grasp the core of MI theory: A response to Visser et al. | url = | journal = Intelligence | volume = 34 | issue = 5| pages = 503\u2013505 | doi = 10.1016/j.intell.2006.04.002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gardner | first1 = Howard | last2 = Moran | first2 = Seana | year = 2006| title = The science of multiple intelligences theory: A response to Lynn Waterhouse | url = | journal = Educational Psychologist | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 227\u2013232 | doi = 10.1207/s15326985ep4104_2 }}</ref>\n\nGardner's theory of multiple intelligences can be seen as both a departure from and a continuation of the last century's work on the subject of human intelligence.  Other prominent psychologists whose contributions variously developed or expanded the field of study include [[Charles Spearman]], [[Louis Thurstone]], [[Edward Thorndike]], and [[Robert Sternberg]].\n\nIn 1967, Professor [[Nelson Goodman]] started an educational program called Project Zero at the Harvard Graduate School of Education, which began with a focus in arts education and now spans throughout a wide variety of educational arenas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pz.harvard.edu/history.php|title=Project Zero: History|work=Pz.harvard.edu|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014215717/http://www.pz.harvard.edu/history.php|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Howard Gardner and David Perkins were founding Research Assistants and later Co-Directed Project Zero from 1972-2000. Project Zero's mission is to understand and enhance learning, thinking, and creativity in the arts, as well as humanistic and scientific disciplines at the individual and institutional levels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harvard Project Zero|url=http://pzweb.harvard.edu/|work=Pzweb.harvard.edu|accessdate=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014215718/http://pzweb.harvard.edu/|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Goodworkteam.jpg|thumb|Goodworkteam|Good Project founders: [[William Damon]], [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]], and Gardner]]\n\nFor almost two decades, in collaboration with [[William Damon]], [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]], and several other colleagues, Gardner has been directing research at The Good Project on the nature of good work, good play, and good collaboration. The goal of his research is to determine what it means to achieve work that is at once excellent, engaging, and carried out in an ethical way. With colleagues Lynn Barendsen, Wendy Fischman, and Carrie James, Gardner has developed curricular toolkits on these topics for use in educational and professional circles.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Educating for Good Work: From Research to Practice| doi=10.1080/00071005.2013.829210|volume=61| issue=4|journal=British Journal of Educational Studies|pages=453\u2013470|year = 2013|last1 = Mucinskas|first1 = Daniel| last2=Gardner| first2=Howard| url=https://www.issuelab.org/permalink/resource/20502}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements and awards==\nIn 1981 Gardner was the recipient of a [[MacArthur Prize Fellowship]]. In 1990 he became the first American to receive the [[University of Louisville]] [[Grawemeyer Award]] in Education.<ref name=grawemeyer.org>{{cite web |title=1990 - Howard Gardner |url=http://grawemeyer.org/education/previous-winners/1990-howard-gardner.html |work=Grawemeyer.org |accessdate=11 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014072135/http://grawemeyer.org/education/previous-winners/1990-howard-gardner.html |archive-date=14 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>   In 1985, The National Psychology Awards for Excellence in the Media, awarded Gardner The Book Award for ''Frames of Mind: The Theory of Multiple Intelligences'', which was published by Basic Books.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eds.b.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?sid=f5a31b19-82de-4d07-b703-f3d90a7580e3%40sessionmgr112&vid=15&hid=126/ |title=National psychology awards for excellence in the media. |accessdate=2014-10-12}}</ref>  In 1987, he received the William James Award from the [[American Psychological Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/en/press/news/howard-gardner-2011-prince-of-asturias-award-for-social-sciences/ |title=Howard Gardner, 2011 Prince of Asturias Award for Social Sciences - The Prince of Asturias Foundation |work=Fpa.es |date= |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref> In 2000 he received a fellowship from the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|John S. Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]].  Four years later he was named an Honorary Professor at [[East China Normal University]] in Shanghai. In the years 2005 and 2008 he was selected by [[Foreign Policy]] and [[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]] magazines as one of the top 100 most influential public intellectuals in the world.<ref name=\"Fpa.es\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fpa.es/en/press/news/howard-gardner-2011-prince-of-asturias-award-for-social-sciences/ |title=Howard Gardner, 2011 Prince of Asturias Award for Social Sciences - The Prince of Asturias Foundation |work=Fpa.es |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> In 2011, he won the [[Prince of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award]] in Social Sciences for his development of multiple intelligences theory.<ref name=\"Fpa.es\"/> In 2015, he received the Brock International Prize in Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brockprize.org/laureates2 |title=Brock International Prize in Education Laureates |work=BrockPrize.org |date= |accessdate=2017-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017032840/http://brockprize.org/laureates2 |archive-date=2016-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe has received 31 honorary degrees from colleges and universities around the world, including institutions in Bulgaria, Canada, Chile, Greece, Hong Kong, Ireland, Israel, Italy, South Korea, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pz.harvard.edu/pis/hg.htm |title=Howard Gardner |work=Pz.harvard.edu |accessdate=2012-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815073200/http://www.pz.harvard.edu/PIs/HG.htm |archivedate=2012-08-15 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHoward Gardner is married to Ellen Winner, Professor of Psychology at Boston College. They have one child, Benjamin. Gardner has three children from an earlier marriage: Kerith (1969), Jay (1971), and Andrew (1976); and five grandchildren: Oscar (2005), Agnes (2011), Olivia (2015), Faye Marguerite (2016), and August Pierre (2019).<ref name=ZeroBio>{{cite web |title=Howard Gardner Project Zero Biography |url=http://pz.harvard.edu/who-we-are/people/howard-gardner|work=Pz.harvard.edu|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Multiple Intelligences Reconsidered |editor-last=Kincheloe |editor-first=Joe L. <!--|author=Joe L. Kincheloe|author2=Kathleen Nolan|author3=Yusef Progler|author4=Peter Appelbaum|author5=Richard Cary|author6=Donald S. Blumenthal-Jones|author7=Marla Morris|author8=Jay L. Lemke|author9=Gaile S. Cannella|author10=Danny Weil|author11=Kathleen S. Berry--> |year=2004 |publisher=Peter Lang |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8204-7098-6 |series=Counterpoints v. 278 |issn=1058-1634 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/multipleintellig0000unse_o8g0 }}\n* {{cite book |title=\"A Blessing of Influences\" in Howard Gardner Under Fire |editor-last=Schaler |editor-first=Jeffrey A. |author=Howard Gardner |year=2006 |publisher=Open Court |location=Illinois |isbn=